{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488551"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:46:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:46:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"477"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/477"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.03,0.08,0.24,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113909"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/477"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95928"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"238"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11495"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113909"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old accountant presents to his general practitioner with dyspnoea, dry cough and reduced exercise tolerance. These symptoms have been present for two years and have been slowly getting worse. He is known to have asthma, which is managed with a daily low dosed inhaled corticosteroid, which he only takes occasionally. He is an ex-smoker with a 15 pack-year history. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is clubbing of his fingers, reduced chest expansion, and crepitations at the lung bases. There is no wheeze. A chest X-ray shows a non-specific reticulonodular pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely aetiology for this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idiopathic","Drug-related","Hypersensitivity","Sarcoidosis","Pulmonary neoplasm"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic\u003C/strong\u003E cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms is most likely. Idiopathicpulmonary fibrosis (IPF) is a chronic and progressive form of interstitial lung disease. IPF primarily occurs in those older than 50 years, occurring most commonly in patients aged 60 to 70 years old. The pathophysiology of IPF is unknown, but various causes have been suggested in literature including genetic susceptibility, environmental and occupational exposure, smoking, GORD and viral infections, leading to repetitive micro-injury to the lung tissue and vasculature, resulting in inflammation and fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESymptoms of IPF are non-specific, but include slow, progressive worsening of lung function, such as dyspnoea, cough and reduced exercise tolerance. Physical examination findings are also non-specific but may include bibasilar mid- to end- inspiratory crackles, end-expiratory squeaks due to bronchiectasis and clubbing of the fingernails in advanced disease. Diagnosis of IPF is based on clinical and radiological findings and pulmonary function testing. All patients with suspicion of IPF should undergo high resolution CT (HRCT) which characteristically reveals reticular opacities, traction bronchiectasis, honeycombing and ground-glass opacities. Pulmonary function testing will show a restrictive picture with impaired diffusion (reduced DLCO).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral medications may cause interstitial lung disease \u2013 some of which include methotrexate, ethambutol and isoniazid (the latter two often used in treatment of tuberculosis). The case stem describes occasional use of inhaled corticosteroid for asthma, but no other drug history. This makes \u003Cstrong\u003Edrug-related \u003C/strong\u003Einterstitial lung disease unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity \u003C/strong\u003Epneumonitis should be suspected in patients with known exposure to a causative agent of the disease or an interstitial lung disease picture without clear aetiology. A history describing recurrent atypical pneumonia and regression of symptoms whilst away from home or work is also suggestive of hypersensitivity\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Epneumonitis. The patient\u2019s dyspnoea and cough is consistent with a diagnosis of hypersensitivity pneumonitis; however, he is an accountant, making risk of occupational exposure low. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E, a multi-system granulomatous disorder, classically presents with bilateral hilar adenopathy, pulmonary reticular or nodular opacities, and skin, joint or eye lesions. It typically presents between 20 and 60 years of age, and is approximately twice as common in women than men. Whilst the patient is male, he is aged 65 and no extrapulmonary features (e.g. erythema nodosum, sarcoidosis hypopigmentation, or lymphadenopathy) were noted on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the patient\u2019s smoking history supports consideration of a \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E in the differential diagnosis, there is no other red flag features (haemoptysis, weight loss, hoarseness of voice) in the history suggestive of lung cancer. The CXR findings of a non-specific reticulonodular pattern also suggest lung cancer is less likely to be the cause of the patient\u2019s symptoms. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis is a common cause of interstitial lung disease in adults over 50.","Interstitial lung disease investigations will show a restrictive picture with reduced DLCO.","High-resolution CT is the investigation of choice for suspected idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis."],"references":["Sharif R. Overview of idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) and evidence-based guidelines. Am J Manag Care. 2017;23(11 Suppl):S176-S82.","King TE. Approach to the adult with interstitial lung disease: clinical evaluation. In: UpToDate, Flaherty KR (Ed), Wolters Kluwer. Updated July 28, 2022. Accessed April 7, 2024. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/approach-to-the-adult-with-interstitial-lung-disease-clinical-evaluation","King TE. Clinical manifestations and diagnosis of sarcoidosis. In: UpToDate, Flaherty KR (Ed), Wolters Kluwer. Updated November 13, 2023. Accessed April 7, 2024. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-sarcoidosis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95928"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"477"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95928"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T12:05:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T12:05:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"477"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":